CommentsTitle: The perfect cable for my own needs!
CommentsDate: Reviewed in the United States January 20, 2021
CommentsContent: Recently I bought a 10gbe card setup for 2 of my computers. My machines are a bit distant from each other and there are live AC power cables in the way. I am well aware that 40gb/s is a bit overkill, but at the same time, I know that AC electromagnetic radiation can interfere with a lot of things.The main selling point for why I got this product was 3 things:1. The insane amount of shielding and protection it has. It's way better than your typical CAT6 or CAT5e cable. (You can tell due to the thickness and the stiffness)2. I needed a cable that is capable of handling a 10gbe transmission speed. I could have gone with CAT6, for sure, but at the same time, 10gb/s is the "maximum" that CAT6 supports up to. There's no guarantee that I would ever "see" the full bandwidth of 10gb/s.3. The price. This cable is super cheap, I was surprised! While the available overhead is quite much, yes, the good thing I can say is this: "At least I'm prepared for USB4!"While I cannot confirm or deny that this cable can handle 40gb/s data transfer rate speeds, I CAN confirm that it handles a full 10gb/s transfer speeds, for sure! When 40gbe network cards come out (or become cheap enough that they're more affordable by the consumer market), I'll update the review and tell you my findings!

CommentsTitle: Bought it for my PS5 and 4K TV
CommentsDate: Reviewed in the United States March 2, 2021
CommentsContent: I currently have AT&T internet and I have the Fiber package which gives me about 1G of internet speed in my area. I personally never had an issue with the WIFI signal on any of my devices or TVs for streaming. However, when I got the new PS5 I just wanted the best experience I could get with the console and the 4K 120 native FPS TV I have. I noticed the slower download speed when downloading digital games and when playing COD Cold War public multiplayer matches. I checked the PS5 internet connection system for WIFI signal and download/upload speeds. Even though I technically had 1G internet and the router was unobstructed and high up for better signal coverage what the PS5 was getting was about 360 download speeds and 60 uploads. This was noticeable in COD and other online games as there would be connection issues and lag. After I bought this 25FT Ethernet cable and set it up to my router I restarted my PS5 and now I consistently get about 990 downloads with about 470 upload speeds. A drastic change over WIFI alone. This makes a difference when gaming online as I have a stable internet connection a low PING. Personally, I recommend this to any serious console or PC gamer forget about a good headphone set they are useless if you are lagging all over the place and have long wait times. Overall, anyone who is looking to gain an increase in the internet connection for either console, PC, TV, or other compatible devices will benefit from buying this cable assuming you have a decent internet plan to start with. Obviously, this ethernet cable can't turn for example a max of 100mbps internet plan into 1G internet speed that is up to you and what you are willing to pay for a month/offered in your area.

CommentsTitle: If you don't want to fall for a scam, buy Cat 6 cables and avoid these cables!
CommentsDate: Reviewed in the United States July 10, 2020
CommentsContent: I bought two of these "Cat 8" cables for the ethernet cable between my router and modem, and between the router and computer. The original cable between my modem and router was a Cat 5e cable that was provided for by the manufacturer of the router. The cable between my router and my computer is a Cat 6 cable from Best Buy. Before I installed both of these cables, I had no issues with streaming, playing video games, and other devices connected to the same network. After installing these two cables, I've had nothing but issues with these cables. They should NOT be sold on the market as Cat 8 standards as they feel stiff and very light as if there are no cables inside. You WILL get severe packet loss on this cables, will drop the connections to streams, at any moment. I've had these longer than the 30 day return policy. I thought it was my computer itself as I uninstalled all networking drivers, followed by reinstalling, and flashed the latest firmware onto the router. I wish I could return these cables as the manufacturer's words do not back up their product. The only words they provide is a FLUKE test that was most likely flawed.

CommentsTitle: I'd give this more starts but, it's not necessary for any regular consumer
CommentsDate: Reviewed in the United States August 7, 2020
CommentsContent: There is really absolutely no point to any consumer buying this cable for use in their home. Cat8 supports up to 25/40Gbps, much faster than any consumer router or even consumer internet supports. Remember: Getting a faster rated ethernet cable does not make your network any faster. Your network is only as fast as the slowest link in the chain. So if your router only handles 1gbps, thats all you are going to get. You'd be far better off saving money and buying a nice Cat6 or even Cat5e cable. Furthermore, Cat8 is not a recognized standard by ISO yet, they are working towards it but it's not a recognized standard yet. It has been ratified by ANSI though.All in all, this cable seems to be decent quality, good for fast networking if you have the switches to support it. I purchased this as a slightly cheaper alternative than other cabling for a 25gbps switch and so far it seems it can maintain the speed, though I purchased a short length of cable. I do not have a longer version of this cable to test and see if it can even reach the distance/speeds that Cat8 should provide according to ANSI.Tl;dr - do not buy this cable unless you have network gear capable of 25 to 40gbps. If you are an average consumer, pick a nice cat5e or cat6 cable. This wont make your Xbox multiplayer gaming any faster.

CommentsTitle: Do not fall for scams like this.
CommentsDate: Reviewed in the United States July 30, 2020
CommentsContent: Don't fall for scams like this. Gold-plated rj45 connectors don't do anything. The 8 individual wires in the inside of the connector is your conductors. Gold plating rj45 connectors is just for show and offers no benefit. It allows the company to over charge you for pointless crap.Residential networking has literally no need for a cable that can handle 40gbs.Cat6 can withstand 1-10gbs uplink that is plenty for any residential and commercial use and the best part is it is cheaper than dirt in bulk.Buy a rj45 crimp set, watch a 5 minute YouTube video and make your own cables.Again, cables like these are an absolute scam.-Data Center Technician.

CommentsTitle: might as well purchase a Cat 5 or 6
CommentsDate: Reviewed in the United States January 12, 2020
CommentsContent: I had never purchased anything above Cat 6 when I recently purchased Cat 8 cable from two different manufacturers.When it seemed that my speed was slower with this Cat 8 cable, I decided to test it. When the initial test confirmed my gut feeling, I decided to do a more rigorous test.For reference, I pay for a 1GB internet speed, so I expected to be limited by that. I compared my WiFi speed as well as Cat 5e, Cat 6, and two different brands of Cat 8For the test I plugged into the same port on the router supplied by my internet provider for each cable.I tested each cable, six times over two days, and eliminated the slowest recorded speed for each.The download results…  this Cat 8 cable was slowest, with results even slower than the Cat 5e by 10.5%The upload results were even worse. This Cat 8 cable was the slowest, with results even slower than the Cat 5e by 13.4%.In case the manufacturer is reading this, the reason I eliminated the slowest recorded speeds from each cable’s test results is because this cable also had the lowest recorded speeds between the Cat 5e, Cat 6 and the Cat 8 from the other manufacturer. I was trying to help this brand’s cable show better results, but it didn’t help.
